    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Everyone Wins</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Barbara Ravage letter about June 3 article on Tony Awards says we should celebrate richness of this season's Tony nominations (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Tonys' All-Star Lineup'' [June 3]:</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Tonys' All-Star Lineup'' [June 3]:</p>
        <p>Call me na√Øve, but I wonder whether serious actors of the caliber of this year's Tony Award nominees are really vying with one another. The words Ben Brantley uses -- ''stiff competition,'' ''the man most likely to beat him'' and so on -- portray a cutthroat race. It's bad enough that we have ''American Idol'' and a 20-month presidential campaign. Must the ''winners and losers'' paradigm infect the theatergoing experience? Can't we just celebrate the richness of this season's Tony nominations and the opportunity audiences have had to see so many gifted actors on so many different stages?</p>
        <p>Barbara Ravage  Orleans, Mass.</p>
        <p>THE TONY AWARDS</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
